{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17473209","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17473209"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T22:05:36+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T22:05:36+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2032"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2032","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2032"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.03,0.28,0.01,0.67,0.01]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2032"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"92943"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2032","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2032"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2032"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"76296"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"10"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1027"},{"type":"tags","id":"4954"},{"type":"tags","id":"4971"},{"type":"tags","id":"11632"},{"type":"tags","id":"11638"},{"type":"tags","id":"11691"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"14959"},{"type":"contributions","id":"31904"},{"type":"contributions","id":"31905"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42435"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44065"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"92943","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/92943"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 17-year-old girl presents to the General Practice clinic with her parents. They express concerns about her lack of energy, irritability, loss of appetite, and poor sleep for the past three weeks. Her parents have noticed that she isolates herself in her room as soon as she gets home from school and goes straight to bed for more than 12 hours per night. She used to enjoy playing netball but recently stopped attending training activities. Earlier this week, her teacher expressed concern as she stopped submitting her assignments and has been disrespectful in class at times. A few weeks ago, her parents found out that she had been drinking alcohol at a party. She admits that she is mourning the loss of her uncle, whom she was very close to. He died from bowel cancer six months ago.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EShe has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. On examination, she appears well. Her vital signs are within normal limits. She appears unkempt and avoids making eye contact. She describes a flat mood with restricted affect. She is easily distracted and appears to be losing focus during the consultation.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Substance abuse","Adjustment disorder","Bipolar disorder","Major depressive disorder","Attention deficit hyperactivity disorder"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with symptoms consistent with \u003Cstrong\u003Emajor depressive disorder\u003C/strong\u003E. She has experienced a depressed mood for at least two weeks, along with loss of interest in activities such as netball. These symptoms fulfil one of the two major DSM-5 criteria for major depressive disorder. Additionally, she exhibits symptoms of psychomotor agitation, poor sleep, loss of appetite, decreased concentration, and low energy. These symptoms meet the remaining minor criteria for diagnosing major depressive disorder according to DSM-5.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAdjustment disorder\u003C/strong\u003E is characterised by depressive symptoms occurring within three months in response to an identifiable stressor. While she is experiencing grief from her uncle\u0027s death six months ago, her symptoms developed only three weeks ago. This suggests that her symptoms are more deep-rooted beyond the identified stressor, aligning more with major depressive disorder rather than adjustment disorder.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAttention deficit hyperactivity disorder\u003C/strong\u003E (ADHD) typically involves issues with concentration, but her presentation lacks other features of ADHD such as hyperactivity and impulsivity. These features usually manifest before age 12.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESubstance abuse\u003C/strong\u003E is characterised by craving, tolerance, and difficulty controlling the use of a substance. Withdrawal symptoms may be present with abrupt cessation. While there is evidence of alcohol consumption, the patient\u0027s alcohol intake appears mild and does not fully explain her symptoms.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBipolar disorder\u003C/strong\u003E involves alternating episodes of depression and mania or hypomania. There is no history of manic episodes in this case, making bipolar disorder less likely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn adolescents, it\u0027s crucial to consider various differential diagnoses when evaluating depressive symptoms. However, the persistence and severity of this patient\u0027s symptoms, along with their impact on her daily functioning, strongly suggest major depressive disorder as the most likely diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["To make a diagnosis of major depressive disorder, the depression must be present for at least two weeks.","Major depressive disorder is characterised by persistent low mood, loss of interest in activities, and associated symptoms such as changes in sleep, appetite, and concentration.","Differential diagnosis of depression in adolescents includes adjustment disorder, substance abuse, and bipolar disorder."],"references":["Diagnostic and Statistical Manual of Mental Disorders, Fifth Edition (DSM-5).In: American Psychiatric Association. Arlington. 2013.","Rowe L, Tonge B. Depression in adolescents. Key issues in assessment and management. Aust Fam Physician. 2003 Apr;32(4):255-60. Available at: https://www.racgp.org.au/getattachment/16f2167c-0380-44c7-b508-427ab594ed13/attachment.aspx"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"76296"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2032"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"76296","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/76296"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-03-20T09:47:26+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-03-20T09:47:26+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2032"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"92943"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"9","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/9"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc76","name":"Paediatrics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-01-16T08:39:03+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"10","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/10"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udfad","name":"Psychiatry","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:46+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"up